To limit the maximum number of characters per line and force a line break in the HTML paragraph after the limit is reached, you can use the `word-wrap` and `word-break` CSS properties.

Here's an example CSS code:

```
p {
  white-space: pre-wrap;
  word-wrap: break-word;
  word-break: break-all;
  max-width: 300px;
  line-height: 1.2em;
}
```

In this example, the CSS properties used are:

- `white-space: pre-wrap`: to preserve any line breaks in the original text.
- `word-wrap: break-word`: this tells the browser to wrap long words onto the next line if they exceed the maximum width.
- `word-break: break-all`: this allows the browser to break words and characters anywhere to fit the given width.
- `max-width: 300px`: this sets the maximum width of the paragraph to 300 pixels.
- `line-height: 1.2em`: this sets the height of each line to 1.2 times the font-size to provide some spacing between lines.

Using these properties together should allow for a maximum number of characters per line, with a line break and word/character breaking for overflow text, while still preserving any original line breaks in the text.

