In React, you can use the `react-router-dom` library to handle navigation between pages and components. Here's an example of how you can use `react-router-dom` to create a button that navigates to an external URL when clicked:

First, you need to install `react-router-dom` by running the following command in your project directory:
```
npm install react-router-dom
```

Next, you can import the `Link` component from `react-router-dom` and use it to create a clickable link:

```jsx
import { Link } from 'react-router-dom';
import { Button } from 'antd';

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Button type="primary">
        <Link to="https://www.example.com" target="_blank">Click me!</Link>
      </Button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

In this example, the `Link` component is wrapped inside an `Ant Design` button. When the button is clicked, it will navigate to the external URL specified in the `to` prop. The `target="_blank"` prop is used to open the URL in a new tab.

By default, `Link` components in `react-router-dom` use client-side routing to navigate to different pages within a React app. But by specifying an external URL and `target="_blank"`, the link will behave like a normal HTML anchor tag and open the URL in a new tab when clicked.

