Here's an example of how you can use `react-scroll` with Ant Design to create a smooth scrolling button:

First, you need to install `react-scroll` by running the following command in your project directory:
```
npm install react-scroll
```

Next, you can import the `Element`, `scroller`, and `Link` components from `react-scroll` and use them to create a clickable scroll-to button:

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import { Button } from 'antd';
import { Element, scroller, Link } from 'react-scroll';

function App() {
  const scrollToSection = () => {
    scroller.scrollTo('section2', {
      duration: 800,
      delay: 0,
      smooth: 'easeInOutQuart'
    });
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <Button type="primary" onClick={scrollToSection}>Scroll to section 2</Button>
      <Element name="section2" className="element" >
        <h2>Section 2</h2>
        <p>This is the second section.</p>
      </Element>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

In this example, the `scroller` function is invoked when the button is clicked, which scrolls smoothly to the specified element. The `name` prop of the `Element` component is set to `"section2"`, which tells `react-scroll` to target that element when scrolling.

You can also customize the scrolling behavior by passing in additional options to the `scroller.scrollTo` function. For example, you can adjust the duration, delay, and easing of the scroll animation to get the desired effect.

Note that you'll need to wrap each section of your page that you want to scroll to in an `Element` component and give it a unique `name` prop that matches the target name used in the `scroller.scrollTo` function.

